306. utrum...ne...an. So often in Plautus, e.g. Capt. 268, Mil. 345, Pseud. 709, Rud. 104. There are three particles, but only two alternatives. Vtrum must still retain in part its old pronominal mean- ing ‘which thing of two' (cf. πότερον), and is used to shew that there is going to be a deliberative question with two alternatives‚ which are introduced respectively by -ne and an.
